:"a","content":["National Geographic Explorer"],"attrs":{"href":"https://www.nationalgeographic.com/impact","target":"_blank"}}," Caitlin Ochs has trekked up and down the Colorado River by foot, raft, car and air to document the impacts of climate change. By her estimate, she’s put in over 10,000 miles driving past surreal Southwestern vistas and austere desert. She’s made visits from the river’s source in the Rocky Mountains to what remains of its delta in the Gulf of California, just south of the U.S.-Mexico border. “It’s been a lot of audiobooks,” Ochs smiles. “I got through a 31-hour book on my last research trip.” Suffice to say, Ochs has developed a particularly profound relationship with the Colorado River Basin."]},{"type":"p","content":["Coming out of these trips are photographs: of the landscape, markedly transformed by ",{"type":"a","content":["record-breaking heat and drought"],"attrs":{"href":"https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/article/the-drought-in-the-western-us-could-last-until-2030","target":"_blank"}}," from climate change, and its people, primarily the farming communities who produce 15% of agriculture for the United States. The region is in its 24th year of megadrought. Studies suggest the Colorado River Basin is seeing its ",{"type":"a","content":["driest period in the last 1,200 years"],"attrs":{"href":"https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/caitochs/colorado-river-drought-west-water","target":"_blank"}},", and with a river that is ",{"type":"a","content":["20% smaller than it was in the 1900s"],"attrs":{"href":"https://www.cnn.com/2023/08/14/us/colorado-river-future-water-climate","target":"_blank"}},", the basin is facing an intensifying water shortage that Ochs argues might be “the largest climate adaptation challenge facing the country.”"]}],{"type":"inline","content":{"name":"Image","props":{"link":{},"caption":{"title":"","credit":"Photograph by Caitlin Ochs","source":"","text":"Afternoon sun looms over farmland in the Imperial