rted by the National Geographic Society through a grant from the ",{"type":"a","content":["World Freshwater Initiative (WFI)"],"attrs":{"href":"https://www.nationalgeographic.org/society/education-resources/protecting-the-worlds-freshwater/","target":"_blank"}},", which is supporting projects related to freshwater conservation, education, and storytelling over the course of five years. American Adaptation aims to focus a lens on the plight of farmers dealing with the intertwined effects of climate change, water shortage and water management policies set in place 100 years ago."," "]},{"type":"p","content":["For years, Ochs has covered environmental issues and pivotal moments in history, including ",{"type":"a","content":["scenes from the COVID-19 pandemic"],"attrs":{"href":"https://www.nytimes.com/2020/05/27/opinion/coronavirus-morgue-trucks-nyc.html","target":"_blank"}}," in New York City and ",{"type":"a","content":["the Black Lives Matter movement"],"attrs":{"href":"https://www.caitlinochs.com/blm","target":"_blank"}}," during the summer of 2020. She considers it a weighty privilege to be co-creating the visual map of this generation’s collective memory: “Any visual journalist is asking people to share their stories and their lives, and that’s a huge responsibility.”"]},{"type":"p","content":["It’s remarkable that someone with little outward relation to the Colorado River has come to have such a fierce determination to tell its stories. Growing up in Seattle, Ochs first came to appreciate the world of photography in high school. Hers came with a fantastic photography teacher and a rare darkroom. “My photographs from that time were not wonderful,” she recalls fondly, but those early days in the darkroom, learning to look at the world through still images and watching the photos emerge, are core memories for Ochs. “That was where I really fell in love with the process of photography. I’m very grateful for that class.”"]},{"type":"p","content":["Darkrooms continued to follow Ochs’s steps. In university, she pursued a degree in environmental policy, doubtful that photography would make for a viable career. But learning of the darkroom on campus, Ochs continued taking photography classes, and, two years into college, shifted focus to journalism in a moment of clarity."]},{"type":"h2","content":["‘Visual anecdotes’ along the Colorado"]},{"type":"p","content":["There’s a thread between each notch in the timeline that Ochs chooses to document. “My work always responds to what we are experiencing,” she reflects. “It’s trying to concisely capture visual anecdotes of our time—not only of what we’re going through, but what we’re feeling, what is impacting our lives.” With the felt effects of climate change reverberating throughout the country and the world, Ochs believes the water crisis in the Colorado River Basin is an urgent story. “The Western United States is changing and nobody knows how, but through this project, I’ve been exploring what these communities are experiencing and how they’re changing.”"]},{"type":"p","content":["Although the megadrought and ",{"type":"a","content":["plummeting water levels of Western reservoirs"],"attrs":{"href":"https://www.usgs.gov/media/images/lake-powell-bathtub-rings-rock-where-lowered-water-levels-have-left-mineral-deposits","target":"_blank"}}," have been semi-regular subjects of environmental headlines in recent years, Ochs believes there is much to the story that gets left out."]},{"type":"p","content":["At home in the midst of the COVID-19 pandemic, Ochs devoted a considerable portion of 2020 to reading and researching the Colorado River. “I got into all the policy, all the history, all the structural stuff,” she recalls, “and the more I learned, the more I was like, ‘This is a huge issue with so many opportunities to tell different aspects of the story, but the same little bits keep getting told. What’s happening in this river basin is so much larger than that.’”"]},{"type":"p","content":["The Colorado River is a critical freshwater system that extends through seven Western U.S. states and northern Mexico. One in 10 people living in the United States look to the river for their water, and agricultural needs rank highest in priority: More than 70% of the river is diverted to farmland. While it may be easy to look at the numbers and suggest ",{"type":"a","content":["cutting water"],"attrs":{"href":"https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/article/big-changes-are-coming-for-the-colorado-river-soonand-they-could-get-messy","target":"_blank"}}," from farms, Ochs finds the issue is nuanced."]},{"type":"p","content":["“Many crops grown in the basin are exported, but if farmland goes out of production, what does that mean for our food security? What does that mean for our rural communities? This is a community that is not only experiencing the impacts of unprecedented heat and shortage, but they’re also under the most pressure to adapt.”"]}],{"type":"inline","content":{"name":"ImageGroup","props":{"images":[{"src":"https://i.natgeofe.com/n/49828eec-3bd5-4dfe-9e46-958b16b0fa0b/05CO2_1783_3x2.jpg","alt":"","sources":[{"src":{"x1":"https://i.natgeofe.com/n/49828eec-3bd5-4dfe-9e46-958b16b0fa0b/05CO2_1783_3x2.jpg?w=374&h=249","x2":"https://i.natgeofe.com/n/49828eec-3bd5-4dfe-9e46-958b16b0fa0b/05CO2_1783_3x2.jpg?w=748&h=498"},"max":374,"nativeWidth":374},{"src":{"x1":"https://i.natgeofe.com/n/49828eec-3bd5-4dfe-9e46-958b16b0fa0b/05CO2_1783_3x2.jpg?w=413&h=275","x2":"https://i.natgeofe.com/n/49828eec-3bd5-4dfe-9e46-958b16b0fa0b/05CO2_1783_3x2.jpg?w=826&h=550"},"max":413,"min":375,"nativeWidth":413},{"src":{"x1":"https://i.natgeofe.com/n/49828eec-3bd5-4dfe-9e46-958b16b0fa0b/05CO2_1783_3x2.jpg?w=718&h=479","x2":"https://i.natgeofe.com/n/49828eec-3bd5-4dfe-9e46-958b16b0fa0b/05CO2_1783_3x2.jpg?w=1436&h=958"},"max":767,"min":414,"nativeWidth":718},{"src":{"x1":"https://i.natgeofe.com/n/49828eec-3bd5-4dfe-9e46-958b16b0fa0b/05CO2_1783_3x2.jpg?w=718&h=479","x2":"htt